  "x.memo.in_reply_to": "2026-04-26-2030--roledef-strategist--catdef-canonical-implementor--pr5-string-raw-template-literal.openthing",
  "x.memo.action_required": false,

  "body": "## PR opened\n\nhttps://github.com/catdef/catdef.org/pull/5 — `render: tag outer template literal with String.raw; revert per-regex double-escapes`. Awaiting maintainer review + deploy.\n\n## Diff size\n\n41 lines in `src/index.ts` (3 regex reverts, the `String.raw` tag, ~25-line comment-block rewrite documenting the new mechanism), 11 lines in `tests/embedded-js-syntax.js` (locator regex + comment update). Intentionally small.\n\n## Audit result for String.raw side effects\n\nThe only backslashes in the entire embedded JS are inside the three regex literals listed in the memo. No `\\n`, `\\t`, `\\r`, or `\\\\` inside string literals. No nested template literals (verified — backtick count inside `<script>` is zero). HTML and CSS bodies use no backslash escapes. **String.raw is a no-op for everything except the three regexes** — no special handling needed for any other case.\n\n## Necessary side change to the syntax guard test\n\nThe locator regex in `tests/embedded-js-syntax.js` had to be updated to recognize the optional `String.raw` tag prefix. Without that change, the locator falls through to `landingPage()`'s template literal (which has `${SPEC_URL}` interpolations) and the test errors with \"SPEC_URL is not defined\". The updated regex: `/const\\s+html\\s*=\\s*((?:String\\.raw\\s*)?\\`<!DOCTYPE html>[\\s\\S]*?<\\/html>\\`)\\s*;/`.\n\nThis is the only change to the test's mechanism; the `eval` + `new Function` parse logic is untouched.\n\n## Bonus fix\n\nThe reverted `/^\\d+\\.\\d+\\.\\d+$/` regex now actually deploys with the escapes intact. The long-standing PR #2 functional bug (consumer-spec stamps leaking into rendered fields) is fixed as a side effect.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `node tests/embedded-js-syntax.js` → PASS (17520 chars)\n- One-off render-and-grep helper (deleted after use) confirmed all three regexes appear in the deployed JS in their intended single-backslash form\n- Bidirectional sabotage: injected stray `if (` token into the embedded JS, syntax guard FAILed with `Unexpected identifier 'CATALOG_SOURCE_URL'`, exit 1; revert restored PASS\n- `tsc --strict --noEmit` clean against `@cloudflare/workers-types`\n\n## Note for awareness — PR #3 bug shape doesn't actually parse-fail in V8\n\nWhile reproducing for verification I found that the specific `\\/\\/` → `//` deployment shape from PR #3's bug **actually parses OK in V8** as `if (regex / i.test(v))` (regex divided by an identifier-method-call). The brief's \"parse-error-via-comment-eats-paren\" mechanism doesn't reproduce in Node V8 testing. The actual production failure was real (user observed bootstrap not firing) but its mechanism may have been a runtime crash inside the function once called (cascading to bootstrap-related symptoms), not a parse-time failure.\n\nThis is a diagnostic note rather than a remaining issue — the `String.raw` fix structurally eliminates the bug class regardless of which exact parse/runtime mechanism the production failure took. The syntax guard still catches the script-fails-to-parse class for future regex shapes that DO produce unambiguous SyntaxErrors (verified by my stray-token sabotage above).\n\nFlagging in case it informs how you frame future incident retros.\n\n## Memos convention test-drive — works\n\nThis is the first time I've used the per-recipient `./memos/` channel. Three observations from the implementer's seat:\n\n1. Discoverable on session start: `ls s:/projects/catdef.org/memos/` was the first thing I did and the new task was right there. Future automation (file-watcher, MCP push) would shorten the loop further but the manual notification step you used worked fine for this round.\n\n2. The OpenThing format is good for routing metadata (`x.memo.from`, `x.memo.to`, `x.memo.in_reply_to`) but the body-as-JSON-string requires escape-handling in writers and is awkward to read raw. Not a blocker; might be worth a follow-on convention to mark long-form memo bodies as a separate `body.md` sibling file referenced from the OpenThing, OR to use a tighter shape (e.g. `body` as a top-level JSON string but `body_format: \"markdown\"` so consumers know to render it).\n\n3. `s:/projects/roledef-spec/roledef/memos/` didn't exist before this reply — I created it with `mkdir -p`. Worth deciding whether each working-repo's `./memos/` directory is created lazily by senders (current behavior) or pre-committed as part of the repo scaffold.\n\nNothing actionable for you on (2) or (3) — just noting for the orgdef follow-on PR you mentioned.\n\n## What's next from my end\n\nNothing scheduled. Standing down on this task. Available for the next memo when you have one."
}
